Incoming livestream: that would let me deduplicate machines, lets you think more critically about the underlying data. And so, when you're analyzing data with AI, I would say think about deduplication, fingerprinting, but especially, AI is really good at signal extraction, pattern matching, identifying the shape of the data.


324
00:37:24.249 --> 00:37:29.958
Incoming livestream: And that ports as well to identifying, like, useful metadata. So we were looking at this data.


325
00:37:29.959 --> 00:37:47.358
Incoming livestream: it's, you know, malware had run on machines and leaked data. Were those machines user laptops, or were they CICD systems? Were those systems containerized? What sort of programming languages were running? What sort of packaging ecosystems? Could we analyze the packages that had been the initial root cause of this incident?


326
00:37:47.359 --> 00:38:00.439
Incoming livestream: And again, the ability to jump from a human trying to identify these patterns to Claude kicking out, you know, 25 different environment variables that signify various CICD platforms I've never heard of is a big level up.


327
00:38:01.839 --> 00:38:02.559
Incoming livestream: But…


328
00:38:02.629 --> 00:38:17.818
Incoming livestream: like, I've been talking about patterns AI can recognize, but I also want to talk about approach, and really advocate for this idea of feedback loops and codification. So when you're working with AI for data analysis, when you're building an AI process.


329
00:38:17.859 --> 00:38:42.548
Incoming livestream: I always try and get to more deterministic methods where possible, right? So, like, we're trying to analyze this data. Instead of asking an AI to iteratively analyze 30 gigabytes, you want to use the AI to generate a more deterministic script, to encode some patterns, some signatures, for scalability, consistency, iteration, backtesting. If you're asking AI to analyze the data over and over again, you're gonna get different small samples.


330
00:38:42.769 --> 00:38:55.549
Incoming livestream: And so instead, you can distill the learnings and codify them into something more deterministic. And so in this case, we found out from that fingerprinting, there were 13,000 unique machines, not 30, 77% of CICD runners.


